xaanti|क्षान्ति
kṣānti  (CII 1), forgiveness.

xapeshvara|क्षपेश्वर
kṣapeśvara  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’.

xaara|क्षार
kṣāra  (IE 7-1-2), ‘five’.

xata|क्षत
kṣata  (EI 23), engraved;<BR>cf. utkīrṇa, udghāṭita, etc. Cf. Prakrit chata (EI 7), ‘written’ (Select Inscriptions, p. 202).

xatrapa|क्षत्रप
Kṣatrapa  (IE 8-2, 8-3;<BR>ML;<BR>HD), feudatory title of foreign origin;<BR>Old Persian Khshathrapāvan, ‘a provincial governor’;<BR>a Satrap. See CII, Vol. II, pp. xxxiv, 23, 28;<BR>Vogel, Ant. Ch. St., p. 166. See Mahākṣatrapa.

xattR|क्षत्तृ
Kṣattṛ  (HD), a chamberlain. See Hist. Dharm., Vol. III, p. 111. According to Manu (X. 16) and Yājñavalkya (I. 94), the offspring of a Kṣatriya woman from a Śūdra male was called Kṣattṛ. This apparently refers to a tribe or community.

xauNii|क्षौणी
kṣauṇī  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’.

xemaraaja|क्षेमराज
Kṣemarāja  (LL), title of a pious king.

xetra|क्षेत्र
kṣetra  (EI 24), a department or committee. (SII 1), a sacred place. Cf. Varāha-kṣetra.

xetrakara|क्षेत्रकर
Kṣetrakara  (EI 12, 15), a cultivator.

xetrapa|क्षेत्रप
Kṣetrapa  (IE 8-3;<BR>HD), same as Kṣetrapāla; supreintendent of the king's Khās Mahāl. See Ind. Ant., Vol. XV, p. 306.

xetrapaala|क्षेत्रपाल
Kṣetrapāla  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 17;<BR>HD), same as Kṣetrapa. Cf. Ep. Ind., Vol. XVII, p. 321.

xetrasiiman|क्षेत्रसीमन्
kṣetra-sīman  (SII 1), explained as ‘a hamlet’.

xiira|क्षीर
kṣīra,  cf. a-puṣpa-kṣīra-grahaṇīya (IE 8-5);<BR>milk which the villagers (probably, the milkmen) were obliged to supply to the king or landlord on occasions and to the touring officials.

xiti|क्षिति
kṣiti  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’.

xitidaana|क्षितिदान
kṣiti-dāna  (EI 23), same as bhūmi-dāna; name of a gift.

xmaa|क्ष्मा
kṣmā  (I 7-1-2;<BR>E 25), ‘one’.

xobha|क्षोभ
kṣobha,  cf. a-lavaṇa-guḍa-kṣobha (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 1);<BR>obligation or trouble.

xoNii|क्षोणी
kṣoṇī  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’.

xudra|क्षुद्र
kṣudra,  cf. Prakrit cūla=culla ‘small’;<BR>prefixed to the names of persons, localities, etc., in order to distinguish them from  others;<BR>e. g., Kṣudra-Mūla, Mahā-Mūla;<BR>Kṣudra-Dharmagiri, Mahā-Dharmagiri.

xudraka|क्षुद्रक
Kṣudraka  (CII 1), a person of a low position;<BR>a poor man. (JNSI, Vol. XVI, p. 44), same as tolaka or draṁkṣaṇa; also spelt kṣudrama.

xudrama|क्षुद्रम
kṣudrama,  see kṣudraka; same as tolaka.

xuNa|क्षुण
kṣuṇa  (CII 2-1), corruption of kṣaṇa.

xuuNa|क्षूण
kṣūṇa  (EI 3), fault or defect. Cf. kṣūṇāni (LP), probably, ‘expenses’;<BR>kṣūṇ-ādika, ‘expenses, etc.’ Cf. mānak-aikaṁ yāvat kṣūṇaṁ na hi (LP), ‘it matters not if there is a loss of one maund only’, i. e. such a case should not be considered a loss.

ku|कु
ku  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’. (CITD), a contraction of Telugu kuṇṭalu or kuccelu, a certain measure of land.

kucha|कुच
kuca  (IE 7-1-2), ‘two’.

kuchaTa|कुचट
kucaṭa  (LP), disturbance of the peace of mind;<BR>cf. Gujarātī kacvāṭ.

kuDya|कुड्य
kuḍya,  probably, ‘a mound’;<BR>see eḍuka.

kula|कुल
kula  (LL), Jain;<BR>a particular section of the Jains. Cf. udhad8īyā-jhumpad8īya-kula (LP), ‘farmers on whom revenue is fixed in a lump sum and who live in huts’. Cf. kulam (EI 25), a land measure;<BR>equal to 2 halas.

kuula|कूल
kūla  (SITI), tax on grains and pulses;<BR>cf. Tamil kirukūlam. Cf. Tamil kūlam (SII 1), a market.

kulabraahmaNa|कुलब्राह्मण
Kula-brāhmaṇa  (SII 1), a family priest.

kulachaarika|कुलचारिक
Kulacārika  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XIII, p. 119, text line 8), wrong reading of Kulavārika=Kulavāra (q. v.).

kulakaraNi|कुलकरणि
Kulakaraṇi  (EI 15;<BR>SII 11-1), a hereditary clerk or officer;<BR>a clerk;<BR>cf. the modern family name Kulkarṇī. The word occurs in the Sūdi inscription of Śaka 981 (Ep. Ind., Vol. XV, p. 91).

kulaakhyaa|कुलाख्या
kul-ākhyā  (CII 3), a family appellation.

kulakuTumbika|कुलकुटुम्बिक
Kula-kuṭumbika  (LP), farmers who are permanently settled.

kulapanjikaa|कुलपञ्जिका
kula-pañjikā,  cf. vaṁśāvalī (IA 30).

kulapati|कुलपति
Kulapati  (EI 9), probably, the head of a school or institution.

kulaputra|कुलपुत्र
Kulaputra  (EI 22;<BR>CII 8), literally, ‘high-born’;<BR>epithet of a nobleman. See Kulaputraka.  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XVIII, p. 156);<BR>explained as ‘the chief architect’.

kulaputraka|कुलपुत्रक
Kulaputraka  (EI 22, 23), a nobleman. See Kulaputra.

kularika|कुलरिक
Kularika  (CII 4), a potter.

kulavaara|कुलवार
Kulavāra  (EI 23), arbitrator;<BR>also called Kulavārika.

kulavaarika|कुलवारिक
Kulavārika,  see Kulacārika.

kulavaay|कुलवाय्
kulavāy  (IE 8-6), Bengali form of kulyavāpa.

kuli|कुलि
kuli  (IE 8-6;<BR>EI 28), Tamil;<BR>a small land measure equal to (1/240) of a pāḍagam.

kuuli|कूलि
kūli  (SII 1), Tamil;<BR>hire.

kulika|कुलिक
Kulika  (EI 15, 35), ‘the head of a guild’;<BR>but cf. Prathama-kulika, ‘the foremost among the Kulikas’, who was the member of a board of administration like the Pañcāyat Board. Some inscriptions of the Gupta age mention a board of administration consisting of the Nagara-śreṣṭhin Sārthavāha, Prathama-Kulika and Prathama-Kāyastha (Ep. Ind., Vol. XV, p. 130), where Kulika seems to mean ‘an artisan’. Kulika is also mentioned as a people probably meaning mercenary soldiers of the Kullu valley (ibid., Vol. XVII, p. 321);<BR>cf. Vogel, Ant. Ch. St., pp. 126-27. (HD), an officer in charge of ten villages who was granted a kula of land for his salary (Manu, VII. 119, and Kullūka thereon);<BR>also ‘an arbitrator as a tribunal’ (IHQ, Vol. XIX, p. 14).

kullaka|कुल्लक
kullaka,  cf. udak-āsīhāra-kullaka; probably, a kind of channel.

kulya|कुल्य
kulya  (IE 8-6), a measure of capacity equal to 8 droṇas. (IE 8-6;<BR>EI 29), a land measure;<BR>shortened form of kulyavāpa.

kulyavaapa|कुल्यवाप
kulyavāpa  (IE 8-6;<BR>EI 28), ‘an area of land requiring one kulya measure of seed grains to be sown’;<BR>a land measure which was not the same in different ages and localities.

kulyaa|कुल्या
kulyā  (EI 13), a channel for irrigation.

kumaara|कुमार
Kumāra  (IE 8-2;<BR>EI 28, 30;<BR>BL;<BR>HD), designation of a prince or the king's heir-apparent;<BR>usually a prince younger than the Yuvarāja (heir-apparent). See CII, Vol. I, pp. 93, 97;<BR>Vol. II, pp. 40, 48. Cf. Devī-kumāra (IA 18;<BR>CII 1).

kumaaraadhiraaja|कुमाराधिराज
Kumārādhirāja  (EI 12, 28), title of a ruler.

kumaaradivaana|कुमारदिवान
Kumāra-Divāna  (BL), possibly, a Divāna or minister enjoying the status of a Kumāra or a Kumāra who was the Divāna. Cf. Kumār-āmātya, Kumāra-mahāpātra. 

kumaaragadiaaNaka|कुमारगदिआणक
kumāra-gadiāṇaka  (CII 4), taken to be the name of a coin by some scholars;<BR>but probably, a tax. Same as kumāra-gadyāṇa.

kumaaragadyaaNa|कुमारगद्याण
kumāra-gadyāṇa  (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 4;<BR>HRS), probably, a tax of one gadyāṇa (i. e. the coin of that name) payable on the occasion of a prince's birth. See kumāra-gadiāṇaka, komarinagadyāṇa, etc. Cf. Tamil kumara-kaccāṇam (EI 21), supposed to be a tax payable in coin for the maintenance of the temple of Kumāra or Subrahmaṇya (SITI). But kumāra-gadyāṇa is found in the records of the Gāhaḍavālas of Vārāṇasī, in whose dominions the god in question was not as popular as in the South.

kumaaraguru|कुमारगुरु
Kumāra-guru  (BL), probably, the royal preceptor enjoying the status of a Kumāra.

kumarakachchaaNam|कुमरकच्चाणम्
kumara-kaccāṇam  (EI 21), a tax;<BR>cf. kumāra-gadyāṇa.

kumaaramahaapaatra|कुमारमहापात्र
Kumāra-mahāpātra  (EI 8-3;<BR>EI 28), a Mahāpātra enjoying the status of a Kumāra or a Kumāra who was the Mahāpātra; cf. Kumār-āmātya.

kumaaraamaatya|कुमारामात्य
Kumār-āmātya  (IE 8-3;<BR>CII 3, 4;<BR>BL;<BR>HD), probably ‘an Amātya enjoying the status of a Kumāra’. Cf. Tamil pil8l8aigal8-tanam (SITI), ‘the status of a Pil8l8ai (prince)’, an officers’ cadre mainly composed of the junior members of the royal family. See Proc. 6th AIOC, pp. 211 ff.;<BR>Vogel, Ant. Ch. St., p. 123. (IE 8-3), in one case, a Kumār-āmātya was at first a Mantrin, but later became a Mahābalādhikṛta; in another case, a Kumārāmātya was also a Mantrin. Cf. Kumāra-mahāpātra, etc. Cf. Kumāra-varga=pil8l8aigal8-tanam (SITI), literally, ‘the status of the Pil8l8ai or prince’;<BR>supposed to be an officers’ cadre composed mainly of the junior members of the royal family. (IE 8-3), also called Khādya(kū*)ṭapākika, Sāndhivigrahika, Mahādaṇdanāyaka, etc., additionally.

kumaaraamaatyaadhikaraNa|कुमारामात्याधिकरण
Kumārāmāty-ādhikaraṇa  (BL), office of the Kumār-āmātya

kumaarapaadiiyaaamaatya|कुमारपादीयआमात्य
Kumārapādīya-āmātya  (BL), an Amātya serving a Kumāra or enjoying the status of a Kumāra. Cf. Kumār-āmātya.

kumaaraasya|कुमारास्य
kumār-āsya  (IE 7-1-2), ‘six’.

kumaaravarga|कुमारवर्ग
Kumāra-varga  (SITI), subordinate chieftains who considered themselves as sons of the king or members of the royal family.

kumaaravRtti|कुमारवृत्ति
kumāra-vṛtti,  cf. Tamil pil8l8ai-vari (SITI), tax for the upkeep of the order of Pil8l8ais or Kumāras (princes). Kumāra-vṛtti occury in the inscriptions of the Western Cālukyas of Kalyāṇa. 

kumaariisaahasa|कुमारीसाहस
kumārī-sāhasa  (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 3, 25;<BR>CII 4), ‘offence against an unmarried girl’;<BR>fine for abducting an unmarried girl;<BR>same as kumārīsāhasa-doṣa.

humaariisaahasadoSha|हुमारीसाहसदोष
humārīsāhasa-doṣa  (EI 32), fine for abducting an unmarried girl.

kumbha|कुम्भ
kumbha  (EI 5), the pinnacle of a temple;<BR>same as kalaśa. See also kumbhaka.

kumbaabhiSheka|कुम्बाभिषेक
kumb-ābhiṣeka  (SII 3), same as Tamil tiru-kkalaśa-muḍittal (SITI), the consecration ceremony of a temple.

kumbhaka|कुम्भक
kumbhaka  (LL), the base of a pillar.

kumosa|कुमोस
kumosa  (Chamba), forced labour.

kuMvara|कुंवर
Kuṁvara  (BL), regional modification of Kumāra.

kaaNam|काणम्
kāṇam  (EI 16), name of a gold coin.

kunci|कुञ्चि
kuñci  (IE 8-6), a measure of capacity usually regarded as equal to eight handfuls.

kuNDa|कुण्ड
kuṇḍa  (EI 23), a spring. (EI 31), a pond.

kuuNDi|कूण्डि
kūṇḍi  (EI 23), a land measure.

kuNDikaa|कुण्डिका
kuṇḍikā  (LP), a reservoir of water.

kunjara|कुञ्जर
kuñjara  (IE 7-1-2), ‘eight’.

kunkumavastra|कुङ्कुमवस्त्र
kuṅkuma-vastra  (ASLV), ‘saffron-coloured cloth’;<BR>sometimes the privilege to wear it was granted to particular persons.

kunnu|कुन्नु
kunnu  (Chamba), also called kunu; a land measure.

kunta|कुन्त
kunta  (Chamba), name of a tax.

kuNTa|कुण्ट
kuṇṭa  (EI 21), a land measure;<BR>cf. guṇṭha.

kuntala|कुन्तल
kuntala  (EI 24), ‘one who wields the spear’.

kunu|कुनु
kunu  (Chamba), also called kunnu; a land measure.

kuupa|कूप
kūpa  (Ep. Ind., Vol. VII, p. 46, note 8), an ordinary well;<BR>cf. vāpī which is a well with a flight of stairs.

kuupadarshaka|कूपदर्शक
Kūpadarśaka  (EI 24), a water-diviner;<BR>an inspector of wells.

kupyagRha|कुप्यगृह
kupya-gṛha  (HRS), a store-house for forest produce as indicated by the Arthaśāstra.

kuura|कूर
kūra,  cf. a-kūra-chullaka-vināśi-khaṭvā-vāsa (IE 8-5);<BR>explained as ‘boiled rice’;<BR>but probably ‘unboiled rice’. The villagers were obliged to supply it to the touring officers of the king. See vodā, siddh-ānna.

kurangamada|कुरङ्गमद
kuraṅga-mada  (IA 18), musk.

kuurma|कूर्म
kūrma  (EI 14), see madhya-kūrma, ‘a plot of land elevated in the middle.’ 

ku|कु
ku r8r8am (IE 8-4), Tamil;<BR>a district or its subdivision;<BR>sometimes the same as nāḍu, but sometimes only the part of a nāḍu.

kuruvinda|कुरुविन्द
kuruvinda,  cf. kur8uvindam (SII 2), an inferior ruby.

kusha|कुश
kuśa,  cf. kuśa-kkāṇam (SITI), Tamil, tax on the potters.

kushala|कुशल
kuśala  (IA 17), used in the sense of puṇya, religious merit;<BR>cf. kuśala-mūla.

kushalamuula|कुशलमूल
kuśala-mūla  (CII 2-1;<BR>ML), ‘the root of merit’;<BR>used to indicate ‘a pious deed’.

kushalin|कुशलिन्
Kuśalin  (CII 3;<BR>SII 3;<BR>IA 9), ‘being in good health’, used in the preamble of charters to indicate the genuineness and validity of the grant made by the donors when they were in a healthy state of body and mind;<BR>epithet of a donor of copper-plate grants to indicate that the charters were issued when the donor was not subject to any disease like madness.

kusuutra|कुसूत्र
kusūtra,  (LP), wrong.

kuuTa|कूट
Kūṭa  (IA 7), cf. Rāṣṭrakūṭa, Deśakūṭa, Grāmakūṭa.

kuuTaka|कूटक
Kūṭaka  (EI 5), probably, headman of the cultivators;<BR>same as Grāmakūṭaka. (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 4, 26), tax for the maintenance of the Kūṭaka; see pravaṇikara-kūṭaka-prabhṛti-samast-ādāya (Ep. Ind., Vol. IV, p. 101). (CII 4), a measure of capacity. (EI 2), a load or measure of salt.

kuuTakolasa|कूटकोलस
Kūṭakolasa  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 29), known from the BhaumaKara records of Orissa;<BR>official designation of uncertain import;<BR>cf. Kūṭa or Kūṭaka.

kutaamra|कुताम्र
ku-tāmra  (IA 30), a fraudulent charter.

kuuTashaasana|कूटशासन
