paagh|पाघ्
pāgh d8ī, cf. talār-ābhāvya.

pagod|पगोद्
pagod, pagoda  (EI 8-8), also called ‘star pagoda’;<BR>English name of the gold coin called hūn (hon) or varāha; probably so called because the coins often bore the representation of a temple called pagod or pagoda by the early European travellers. The word seems to have been derived from Sanskrit bhagavat or bhagavatī meaning the deities worshipped in the temples and also often figuring on the coins. Cf. ‘ṭaṅkakas stamped with the figure of the Bhagavat’ (Bhandarkar's List, No. 2033). Cf. Cīna-pagoda (SII 12), ‘the Chinese temple’;<BR>name of a Buddhist shrine at Nāgapaṭṭanam.

