sandhyaa|सन्ध्या
sandhyā  (CITD), the morning, noon and evening prayers of a Brāhmaṇa. (CII 3;<BR>IA 17), a period at the commencement of each of the four Hindu ages;<BR>the sandhyā of the Kali-yuga lasts for 36,000 years of men, and is still running;<BR>cf. sandhyāṁśa.

sandhidiipa|सन्धिदीप
sandhi-dīpa,  cf. sandi-vil8akku (SITI), a twilight lamp;<BR>generally lighted in the temples in the evening, but sometimes in the morning;<BR>same as sandhyā-dīpa.

sandhyaaMsha|सन्ध्यांश
sandhy-āṁśa  (AI 17), a period at the end of each of the four yugas, the sandhy-āṁśa of the Kali-yuga to last for 36,000 human years.

sandoha|सन्दोह
sandoha,  cf. a-puṣpa-kṣīra-sandoha (IE 8-5), realisation or levy (cf. a-puṣpa-kṣīra-grahaṇīya).

sangaDiraxaapaalaka|सङ्गडिरक्षापालक
Saṅgaḍi-rakṣā-pālaka  (EI 6), an officer;<BR>the meaning of saṅgaḍi is uncertain.

sangam|सङ्गम्
saṅgam,  Tamil;<BR>same as Sanskrit saṅgha; an assembly of ancient Tamil poets;<BR>the name given to an assembly of poets reported in tradition to have functioned in three different periods. The poets are believed to have been both literary critics and composers. Literary compositions of the age were later collected and compiled into anthologies known as Eṭṭuttokai, Pattuppāṭṭu and Padineṇkīl8kaṇakku according to their contents and size. The saṅgam is stated to have flourished at Kūḍal (also called Madurai in later literature) in the first and last period and at Kavāṭapuram in the middle period. The latest limit for the first two anthologies may be placed round about 700 A.D. See M. S. Purnalingam Pillai, Tamil Literature, pp. 14-18;<BR>S. Vaiyapuri Pillai, History of Tamil Language and Literature, p. 38.

saNGgha|सङ्घ
saṅgha  (ASLV), a social organisation. (BL), a community of Buddhist monks;<BR>the Buddhist Church. (HA), a Jain congregation;<BR>the Jain Church (made up of four constituents, viz. sādhu, sādhvī, śrāvaka and śrāvikā) also called Jaina-saṅgha; a group of pilgrims going together on  pilgrimage under the leadership of a Saṅghapati (q. v.). (EI 22), a tribe. Cf. Tamil saṅgam (q. v.).

saNGghapati|सङ्घपति
Saṅgha-pati  (EI 8;<BR>BL), title of the leader of a group of Jain pilgrims to a holy place, who bears all the expenses of the whole group;<BR>same as Saṅghaprabhu, Saṅghavī, etc. Cf. the modern Jain family name Siṅghī.

saNGghaprabhu|सङ्घप्रभु
Saṅgha-prabhu  (EI 8), Jain;<BR>same as Saṅghapati, etc.

saNGghaprakRta|सङ्घप्रकृत
Saṅgha-prakṛta  (LL), Buddhist;<BR>probably, a supporter of the saṅgha; translated as ‘commissioners of the community’ (Lüders, Mathurā Inscriptions., pp. 84 ff.).

saNGgharaaja|सङ्घराज
Saṅgharāja  (EI 8), Buddhist;<BR>title of the principal ecclesiastical functionary in Burma.

saNGghaaraama|सङ्घाराम
saṅghārāma  (EI 4;<BR>ML;<BR>LL), a Buddhist monastery.

saNGghasthavira|सङ्घस्थविर
Saṅgha-sthavira  (LL), an Elder of the Buddhist congregation. Cf. Sthavira.

saNGghaaTa|सङ्घाट
saṅghāṭa, saṅghāṭā  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIII, p. 248), cf. pāda-saṅghāṭa or pāda-saṅghāṭā, ‘a pair of feet (i. e. foot-marks)’.

saNGghaaTii|सङ्घाटी
saṅghāṭī  (EI 25), robe of a Buddhist monk.

saNGghavii|सङ्घवी
Saṅghavī  (BL;<BR>HA;<BR>PJS), derived from Sanskrit Saṅghapati (q. v.);<BR>designation of the leader of a saṅgha or group of Jains;<BR>the leader of a group of Jain pilgrims, who bears expenses of all the pilgrims going with him (cf. the Jain family name Siṅghī).

sangrahaNa|सङ्ग्रहण
saṅgrahaṇa  (IE 8-5), adultery.

sangrahiitR|सङ्ग्रहीतृ
Saṅgrahītṛ  (HD), explained by some as ‘a treasurer or charioteer’ (Hist. Dharm., Vol. III, p. 111);<BR>probably, collector of the king's grain share. Cf. Ghoshal, H. Rev. Syst., p. 9.

shaani|शानि
śāni  (SITI), Dravidian;<BR>wife;<BR>a term by which a Brāhmaṇa woman was referred to.

shanivaaramaNDapa|शनिवारमण्डप
śanivāra-maṇḍapa  (A.R. Ep., 1958-59, p. 13), name of a building attached to a temple apparently meant for some function held there on Saturdays;<BR>cf. vaikkāṇikku-maṇḍapa under maṇḍapa.

sanjaati|सञ्जाति
sañjāti  (LP), cf. rāja-sañjātyāṁ kartavyaḥ, ‘may be made a government property.’

sanjiivaraaja|सञ्जीवराज
Sañjīva-rāja,  cf. Sañjīvarāyar (SITI), name of Hanumān.

sankaachitaka|सङ्काचितक
saṅkācitaka  (IE 8-8), a loop;<BR>same as Sanskrit kāca.

sankalpa|सङ्कल्प
saṅkalpa  (Chamba), also called saṅkalpa-hast-odaka; libation of water;<BR>donation.

sankara|सङ्कर
saṅkara  (EI 9), also called saṅkuru; a double sack. 

shankaraaxi|शङ्कराक्षि
śaṅkar-ākṣi  (IE 7-1-2), ‘three’.

sanketa|सङ्केत
saṅketa,  cf. sva-saṅketa (LP), ‘one's own special arrangement’.

shaNGkha|शङ्ख
śaṅkha  (CII 3, etc.), conch-shell as ane mblem on seals;<BR>cf. śaṅghu (ASLV), the use of which was sometimes granted by kings to their favourites as a privilege.

shaNGkhadhaaraa|शङ्खधारा
śaṅkhadhārā,  cf. śaṁkudhāra (CITD);<BR>Telugu;<BR>continuous blowing of the conch-shell. See Śaṅkhadhārin.

shaNGkhadhaarin|शङ्खधारिन्
Śaṅkhadhārin  (IE 8-3), blower of the conch-shell;<BR>sometimes mentioned as a Pātra.

shaNGkhakaara|शङ्खकार
Śaṅkhakāra  (EI 28), also called Śāṅkhika (q. v.);<BR>maker of conch-shell bangles.

shaNGkhika|शङ्खिक
Śaṅkhika, Śāṅkhika  (EI 24, 28), same as Śaṅkhakāra (q. v.), worker on conch-shells.

sankramaNa|सङ्क्रमण
saṅkramaṇa  (CII 3;<BR>IA 17), also called saṅkrānti; the entrance of the sun into a sign of the zodiac;<BR>regarded as an auspicious time for performing religiousduties.

sankraanti|सङ्क्रान्ति
saṅkrānti  (CII 3;<BR>IA 17), same as saṅkramaṇa (q. v.). (IE 7-1-2), ‘twelve’.

ShaNmukhabaahu|षण्मुखबाहु
ṣaṇmukha-bāhu  (IE 7-1-2), ‘twelve’.

sannaaha|सन्नाह
sannāha  (LP), armour.

sannidhaatR|सन्निधातृ
Sannidhātṛ  (EI 27), official in charge of the receipt of various articles into the king's treasury, according to some (HRS);<BR>superintendent of the construction of the royal treasury, store houses, etc., according to others. See Arthaśāstra, II. 5;<BR>cf. I. 10 and 12;<BR>Ep. Ind., Vol. VIII, pp. 138, 141;<BR>Vol. XI, pp. 93-94.

sannidhi|सन्निधि
sannidhi,  cf. sannadi (SII 1), presence of a deity;<BR>the front of a temple.

sanniyuktaka|सन्नियुक्तक
Sanniyuktaka  (Ind. Ant., Vol. XVII, p. 11, text line 14), same as Tanniyuktaka or a mistake for it.

sanskrit|सन्स्क्रित्
Sanskrit,  Anglicised form of Saṁskṛta, the name of the sacred language of the Indians.

santa|सन्त
santa  (CITD), Telugu-Kannaḍa;<BR>a fair or market day. (EI 14), name of a measure or a coin;<BR>probably, a small coin (Ep. Ind., Vol. XV, p. 309).

santai|सन्तै
santai  (ASLV), a weekly fair.

santaka|सन्तक
santaka  (EI 27;<BR>CII 3), Prakrit;<BR>‘belonging to’;<BR>sometimes Sanskritised as satka. Sometimes santaka (also santika apparently used in the same sense) has been regarded as  meaning ‘a territorial unit’;<BR>supposed similarly to mean ‘a servant’ (EI 23) or ‘an officer’ (EI 24).

saantakika|सान्तकिक
Sāntakika  (IE 8-3), official designation of uncertain import.

santaana|सन्तान
santāna  (SITI), lineage. (BL), cf. a Jain religious teacher described as belonging to the paṭṭa of another teacher and the santāna of a third teacher. (IA 20), used in the sense of āmnāya or kula-krama. (EI 6), same as santānaka, santati; seven in number.

santaanashaapa|सन्तानशाप
santāna-śāpa  (SITI), curse that prevents progeny.

santaanikashaiva|सन्तानिकशैव
Santānika-śaiva  (SITI), Śaivas who belong to the line of ācāryas of the santāna-kuravar.

santati|सन्तति
santati  (SITI), lineage. Cf. also sapta-santati (EI 14) and santānaka (under santāna).

santatipravesham|सन्ततिप्रवेशम्
santati-praveśam  (SITI), ‘from generation to generation’.

shaanti|शान्ति
Śānti,  a priest in a temple;<BR>cf. Tamil-Sanskrit Mel-śānti; also cf. Śāntikāra, of which Śānti seems to be an abbreviation.

shaanti|शान्ति
śānti  (EI 33), a propitiatory rite;<BR>cf. śānty-āgāra.

santika|सन्तिक
santika  (EI 25), proximity, presence.

shaantikaara|शान्तिकार
Śāntikāra  (SITI), a temple priest;<BR>also known as Śāntiyaḍigal and Śānti-śeyyān.

santiiraNaa|सन्तीरणा
santīraṇā,  cf. artha-santīraṇā (CII 1), despatch of business.

shaantivaarika|शान्तिवारिक
Śānti-vārika  (EI 12, 30, 33), priest in charge of the performance of propitiatory rites or the priest who provides for śānti-vāri, ‘propitiatory water’.

shaantyaagaara|शान्त्यागार
śānty-āgāra  (EI 12, 30), room wherein a bath is taken with the propitiatory water after a sacrifice;<BR>the room for performing propitiatory rites. See Śāntyāgārika, Śāntyāgār-ādhikṛta.

shaantyaagaaraadhikRta|शान्त्यागाराधिकृत
Śāntyāgār-ādhikṛta  (EI 30), priest in charge of the room for the performance of propitiatory rites. Cf. śānty-āgāra, Śāntyāgārika.

shaantyaagaarika|शान्त्यागारिक
Śāntyāgārika  (EI 30), same as Śāntyāgār-ādhikṛta.

shaonanoshao|स्हओननोस्हओ
Shaonano Shao  (EI 30), known from the legend of Kuṣāṇa coins;<BR>same as Sāhānuṣāhī (q. v.), Persian Shāhān Shāh.

sapaadalaxa|सपादलक्ष
Sapādalakṣa  (IE 8-4), name of two territories so called with reference to the theoretical number of villages in each of them. Cf. Pādonalakṣa.

sapiNDiikaraNashraaddha|सपिण्डीकरणश्राद्ध
sapiṇḍīkaraṇa-śrāddha  (CII 4), a ceremony.

saptaxetra|सप्तक्षेत्र
sapta-kṣetra  (IA 19), Jain;<BR>seven spheres of action.

saptamachakravartin|सप्तमचक्रवर्तिन्
Saptama-cakravartin  (LP), ‘the seventh emperor’, i. e. the ruling monarch;<BR>according to the Abhidhānacintāmaṇi, the six  older Cakravartins are: Māndhātā Dhundhumāraś = ca Hariścandraḥ Purūravāḥ | Bharataḥ Kārtavīryaś = ca ṣaḍ = ete cakravartinaḥ ||

saptamaatR|सप्तमातृ
Sapta-mātṛ  (EI 23), the seven Divine Mothers.

saptaamaatya|सप्तामात्य
Sapt-āmātya  (EI 27), an officer in charge of seven departments. Cf. Pañca-karaṇ-ādhikṛta, etc.

saptaambhodhi|सप्ताम्भोधि
sapt-āmbhodhi  (EI 16), name of a mahādāna; same as saptasāgara.

saptaanga|सप्ताङ्ग
sapt-āṅga  (CII CITD), the seven constitutent parts of a kingdom, viz., king, ministers, allies, treasury, territory, forts and forces.

saptasaagara|सप्तसागर
sapta-sāgara  (EI 24), name of a mahādāna; same as saptāmbhodhi.

saptasantaana|सप्तसन्तान
sapta-santāna  (SITI), also called sapta-santati; merit equal to that obtainable through progeny from their performance of seven kinds of great deeds, viz. digging of tanks, hoarding of treasure, founding of agrahāras, erection of temples, creation of flower gardens, getting literary works written by poets, and the establishment of Choultries. An inscription (Ep. Ind., Vol. III, pp. 88 ff.) mentions the following seven meritorious acts a man ought to perform during his lifetime;<BR>viz. procreation of sons, accumulation of wealth, planting of groves, helping people (Brāhmaṇas) to marry, getting poems composed, erection of temples and excavation of tanks.

saptasantati|सप्तसन्तति
sapta-santati  (SITI), same as sapta-santāna.

saptavidhi|सप्तविधि
sapta-vidhi  (LP), probably, seven kinds of defects.

shara|शर
śara  (IE 7-1-2), ‘five’.

saaraa|सारा
sārā  (EI 9;<BR>LP), care;<BR>cf. etair = aṣṭabhir = goṣṭhikaiḥ…sārā karaṇīyā, ‘[this place of worship]<BR>has to be taken care of by the following eight trustees’. Cf. also Gujarātī sāravār. (EI 8, 11), supervision.

sharabhanga|शरभङ्ग
Śarabhaṅga  (IE 8-3;<BR>8-8;<BR>EI 23), a leader of forces;<BR>an officer of the military department;<BR>possibly, a military governor;<BR>same as Persian Sarhang and Hindī Serāṅg; also spelt Sarabhaṅga and Sarobhaṅga; Wilson's Glossary explains Sarhang as ‘a commander’ and says, “but [it is]<BR>generally applied in India to the headman of a native crew, whether on board a ship or a boat;<BR>also to the headman of a gang of natives attached to artillery, dragging guns, or to the army in general, as tent-pitchers, and the like, or to the head of gangs of a superior order of labourers employed in public or private works, in docks, buildings,  etc.’ Cf. Vogel, Ant. Ch. St., pp. 123, 166 (spelt Sarobhaṅga), Ind. Cult., Vol. VII, p. 309. Kane (Hist. Dharm., Vol. III, p. 1005) is certainly wrong when he thinks that it may be connected with śarayantra and Śarayantrin (a title bestowed in Mithilā upon a very learned man who faced the ordeal of answering satisfactorily all questions on any śāstra put to him by learned Ācāryas and also the questions put by common people). See Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXV, pp. 95. ff. See Sarāṅgha, Sarāhang, etc.

saaradaa|सारदा
Sāradā,  name of the alphabet which developed out of late Brāhmī and was prevalent in the Kashmir region.

saraahang|सराहन्ग्
Sarāhang  (IA 20), also called Sarang, Sarhang, etc. See Sarāṅgha, Śarabhaṅga.

sharaNaagatavajrapanjara|शरणागतवज्रपञ्जर
Śaraṇāgata-vajrapañjara  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIII, p. 317), ‘the impregnable shelter for one who seeks for it’;<BR>a subordinate title of the Kannaḍa-speaking area;<BR>used by the Sena kings of Bengal because they hailed from the same region.

sarang|सरन्ग्
Sarang  (IA 20), also called Sarhang, Sarāhang, etc.;<BR>see Sarāṅgha, Śarabhaṅga, etc.

saraaNGgha|सराङ्घ
Sarāṅgha  (IE 8-3), Persian Sarhang and Indian Śarabhaṅga, Serāṅg, etc. cf. Giligittā-sarāṅgha, ‘the chief of the army at Gilgit’, in the Hatun inscription of Paṭoladeva (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXX, p. 228).

sarasvatiibhaaNDaara|सरस्वतीभाण्डार
Sarasvatī-bhāṇḍāra  (EI 25;<BR>SITI), a library. Cf. Sarasvatī-bhāṇḍārika.

sarasvatiibhaaNDaarika|सरस्वतीभाण्डारिक
Sarasvatī-bhāṇḍārika  (EI 25), librarian. Cf. Sarasvatībhāṇḍāra.

sharayantra|शरयन्त्र
śarayantra,  Maithilī;<BR>test [prevalent in Mithilā]<BR>of the scholarship of one who is prepared to answer any question on any śāstra put to him by any other scholar or by the common people. See Proc. AIOC, Benares, 1943;<BR>Kane, Hist. Dharm., Vol. III, p. 1005.

sharayantraka|शरयन्त्रक
śarayantraka  (IE 3-1), same as sūtra; the string passing through the hole in the leaves of manuscripts for holding them together (Vāsavadatta, Hall's ed., p. 250).

sharayantrin|शरयन्त्रिन्
Śarayantrin  (EI 35), one who has been successful in the śarayantra test of Mithilā. See śarayantra.

saarayitvaa|सारयित्वा
sārayitvā  (LP), ‘having finished’;<BR>cf. Gujarātī sārvuṁ, ‘to accomplish’.

saardhancara|सार्धञ्चर
Sārdhañcara, Sārdhañcarī  (LL), companion of a Jain monk.

saardhaMvihaarin|सार्धंविहारिन्
Sārdhaṁvihārin,  cf. Sādhyavihāri (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIV,  p. 10), Pāli saddhivihāri; one's fellow-priest living at the same monastery;<BR>a fellow-student. Cf. F. Edgerton, Bud. Hyb. Sans. Gram. Dict., Vol. II, p. 593. See Sadhryagvihārin.

sarhang|सर्हन्ग्
Sarhang  (IE 8-3;<BR>IA 20), Persian;<BR>see Śarabhaṅga, etc.

shariira|शरीर
śarīra  (SITI), person;<BR>individual. (EI 24;<BR>ML), corporeal relies of the Buddha.

sarobhanga|सरोभङ्ग
Sarobhaṅga  (IE 8-3), same as Śarabhaṅga or Sarabhaṅga (q. v.).

sarpa|सर्प
sarpa  (IE 7-1-2), ‘eight’.

sarpabali|सर्पबलि
sarpa-bali  (IA 19), an offering in snake-worship.

sarShapa|सर्षप
sarṣapa,  a small unit of measurement;<BR>sometimes specified as ‘red’ (JNSI, Vol. XVI, p. 48).

saarthavaaha|सार्थवाह
Sārthavāha  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 24, 31;<BR>BL;<BR>LL), a trader, a merchant;<BR>designation of a member of the mercantile community represented on an administrative board like the Pañcāyat.

saarthavaahinii|सार्थवाहिनी
Sārthavāhinī  (EI 1, 24), wife of a merchant (Sārthavāha) or a female merchant.

saarthavahitra|सार्थवहित्र
sārtha-vahitra  (IE 8-3), probably, a cart-load of articles for sale.

saaruupya|सारूप्य
sārūpya  (CITD), assimilation in the deity, one of the four states of mukti.

saarvabhauma|सार्वभौम
Sārvabhauma  (EI 7, 27, 30, 32), title of imperial rulers.

sarvaabhyantarasiddhi|सर्वाभ्यन्तरसिद्धि
sarv-ābhyantara-siddhi  (IA 19;<BR>SII 11-1), a fiscal term denoting full and complete right of enjoyment of agricultural income or internal revenue or taxes to be paid to the village authorities;<BR>cf. sarv-ābhyantara-siddhyā (IA 18), also abhyantara-siddhi.

sarvadaNDanaayaka|सर्वदण्डनायक
Sarva-daṇḍa-nāyaka  (CII 3;<BR>IA 9;<BR>IA BL), official designation;<BR>‘lord of all the forces’;<BR>cf. Samasta-sainy-ādhipati. See Daṇḍa-nāyaka, Mahādaṇḍanāyaka, Sarva-mahā-daṇḍanāyaka. Cf. Ind. Ant., Vol. VIII, p. 19;<BR>Vol. IX, p. 167.

sarvadeshaadhikaarin|सर्वदेशाधिकारिन्
Sarva-deś-ādhikārin  (AI 7), chief minister;<BR>see Deśādhikṛta, Sarv-ādhikārin, etc.

sarvaadhikaaraadhikRta|सर्वाधिकाराधिकृत
Sarv-ādhikār-ādhikṛta  (EI 31), chief minister or administrator;<BR>same as Sarv-ādhikārin, Sarv-ādhyakṣa, etc.

sarvaadhikaarakaraNa|सर्वाधिकारकरण
Sarv-ādhikāra-karaṇa  (EI 30), probably, the office of the chief secretary, administrator or minister.

sarvaadhikaaraniyukta|सर्वाधिकारनियुक्त
Sarv-ādhikāra-niyukta  (EI 32), official designation;<BR>same as Sarv-ādhikārin, Sarv-ādhyakṣa, etc.

sarvaadhikaarin|सर्वाधिकारिन्
Sarv-ādhikārin  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 19;<BR>CII 4;<BR>HD), prime minister (cf. Rājataraṅgiṇī, VII. 568);<BR>minister plenipoten tiary or viceroy;<BR>sometimes also called Senāpati, Mahāpradhāna, Hiriya-bhaṇḍāgārin, Mahāsāmanta, Sen-ādi-bāhattara-niyogādhipati, Daṇḍanāyaka, Mahāpasāyita, Amātya, Paramaviśvāsin or Mahāpramaviśvāsin, etc., additionally. (IE 8-3), a governor or chief administrator (cf. ‘the Sarvādhikārin of Hagaraṭage-300’).

sarvaadhyaxa|सर्वाध्यक्ष
Sarv-ādhyakṣa  (EI 24, 27;<BR>CII 3), literally, a general superintendent;<BR>probably, the chief minister or administrator;<BR>same as Sarv-ādhikārin.

sarvaadhikRta|सर्वाधिकृत
Sarv-ādhikṛta  (HD), same as Sarv-ādhikārin, etc. Cf. Ep. Ind., Vol. XIV, pp. 360, 362. See Mahāsarvādhikṛta.

sarvaagrahaara|सर्वाग्रहार
sarv-āgrahāra  (EI 21), same as sarva-mānya.

sarvajaata|सर्वजात
sarva-jāta,  cf. sarva-jātaa-bhoga-nirastyā (EI 8-5), ‘with all kinds of the [king’s]<BR>rights renounced’.

sarvamaanya|सर्वमान्य
sarva-mānya  (IE 8-5, SITI;<BR>CITD), a free tenure;<BR>a rent-free holding;<BR>land exempted from taxes;<BR>lands and villages fully exempt from all taxes. This corresponds to the ir8aiyili class of land mentioned in the Col13a inscriptions. Often this is associated with aṣṭa-bhoga, i. e. the eight forms of enjoying the land. For a discussion of this form of land tenure, see JAHRS, Vol. X, pp. 123-32. It is noteworthy that even the so-called tax-free (ir8aiyili) lands paid to the king certain dues of the nature of taxes. See K. A. Nilakanta Sastri, The Col13as, 2nd ed., pp. 534-35. See sarva-namasya, etc.

sarvamedha|सर्वमेध
sarva-medha  (EI 4), name of a sacrifice.

sarvanamaskRta|सर्वनमस्कृत
sarva-namaskṛta  (IA 8), same as sarva-namasya.

sarvanamasya|सर्वनमस्य
sarva-namasya  (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 23;<BR>CITD), a rent-free holding;<BR>same as sarva-mānya, sarva-namaskṛta, namasya-vṛtti.

sarvaniyoga|सर्वनियोग
sarva-niyoga  (EI 7), exclusive property.

sarvasainyaadhikaarin|सर्वसैन्याधिकारिन्
Sarva-sainy-ādhikārin  (IE 8-3), commander-in-chief;<BR>cf. Maneya-samasta-sainy-ādhipati, commander of all the soldiers in the royal household;<BR>also cf. Sarva-daṇḍa-nāyaka.

sarvasvaharaNa|सर्वस्वहरण
sarvasva-haraṇa  (SITI), forfeiture of one's entire property.

sarvatantraadhikRta|सर्वतन्त्राधिकृत
Sarva-tantr-ādhikṛta  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXIV pp. 144-45), a superintendent of all departments;<BR>but tantra is used in South Indian records in the sense of ‘the army’. See tantra, Tantrādhikārin, etc.

sarvatobhadra|सर्वतोभद्र
sarvatobhadra  (EI 9), a building having doors on all the four sides. 

sarvatobhadrikaa|सर्वतोभद्रिका
sarvatobhadrikā  (LL;<BR>HA), quadruple image showing a Jina (or several Jinas) on each of the four faces;<BR>same as caumukha.

sarvavaadinaayaka|सर्ववादिनायक
Sarvavādināyaka  (EI 10), explained as ‘superintendent of the intelligence department’;<BR>probably, ‘the chief court Pandit.’

sarvaaya|सर्वाय
sarv-āya  (EI 15), all the usual ducs.

sarviiya|सर्वीय
sarvīya  (EI 13), ‘good to all’.

shaasana|शासन
śāsana  (EI 19;<BR>IA 20), order, a royal edict;<BR>any royal record (cf. vijaya-śāsana). (IE 8-4;<BR>EI 13, 23;<BR>CII 3;<BR>BL), a charter;<BR>land or village granted by a charter;<BR>rent-free land or village;<BR>sometimes suffixed to the names of localities which were once rentfree holdings. See also tāmra-śāsana, a technical term for a deed of conveyance on copper-plates. (EI 9, 10), a doctrine;<BR>religion or religious faith.

shaasanabaddha|शासनबद्ध
Śāsana-baddha  (SITI), people bound by a royal charter;<BR>original grantees of a charter.

shaasanabhaaNDaarin|शासनभाण्डारिन्
Śāsana-bhāṇḍārin  (EI 25), official designation;<BR>cf. Śāsanādhikārin, etc.

shaasanadevii|शासनदेवी
Śāsanadevī  (IA 18), divine female messenger of a Jain Arhat;<BR>same as Śāsana-sundarī.

shaasanaadhikaarika|शासनाधिकारिक
Śāsan-ādhikārika  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XII, p. 155, text line 85), same as Śāsan-ādhikārin, etc.;<BR>officer in charge of grants (or their writing or issue), mentioned along with Dān-ādhikārin, ‘officer in charge of gifts’.

shaasanaadhikaarin|शासनाधिकारिन्
Śāsan-ādhikārin  (EI 28, 31), officer in charge of royal grants or their issue, who was often the writer of documents;<BR>same as Śāsan-ādhikārika, etc.

shaasanapaTaa|शासनपटा
śāsana-paṭā  (Chamba, etc.), charter;<BR>same as Sanskrit śāsana-paṭṭaka.

shaasanamaryaadaa|शासनमर्यादा
śāsana-maryādā  (EI 15), specification of privileges by a charter.

shaasanaardhika|शासनार्धिक
śāsan-ārdhika  (IE 8-5;<BR>12, 28), name of a levy;<BR>probably, the half of the cultivator's share of the produce of the land in the gift village.

shaasayitR|शासयितृ
Śāsayitṛ  (EI 12;<BR>BL), one who is responsible for getting a royal grant executed;<BR>cf. Dūtaka, Lekhayitṛ, Ājñāpti.

shaasanasancaarin|शासनसञ्चारिन्
Śāsana-sañcārin  (EI 8, 24), same as Ājñā-sañcārin; an official messenger.

shaasanasundarii|शासनसुन्दरी
