tailaghaaNaka|तैलघाणक
taila-ghāṇaka  (EI 19), oil mill.

tailaparNikaa|तैलपर्णिका
taila-parṇikā  (EI 24), explained as ‘leaves producing oil’.

tailikaraaja|तैलिकराज
Tailika-rāja  (EI 23), ‘chief of a guild of oilmen’;<BR>designation of the chairman of the oilmen's guild.

tairthika|तैर्थिक
Tairthika  (EI 32), same as Tīrthika, a priest [of the nonBuddhists]. (IE 8-3), cf. Tūthika (EI 1;<BR>LL), ferry-officer or officer in charge of the places of pilgrimage.

taajika|ताजिक
Tājika Tajjika  (EI 23, 32), Tājiya, Tāyika; an Arab.

Taakaa|टाका
ṭākā,  Bengali form of ṭaṅka, meaning a silver coin (rupee) and also money.

Thaakorkhaanaa|ठाकोर्खाना
ṭhākorkhānā  (HA), same as balānaka.

taxaachaarya|तक्षाचार्य
takṣ-ācārya,  cf. Tamil tacc-ācāriyam (SITI), the status of the master carpenter;<BR>chief of the carpenters. Cf. tacc-ācāriyakkāṇi, the right of officiating as the chief carpenter, as also the stone-mason of a temple;<BR>the land set apart for the enjoyment of the holder of that office.

taxan|तक्षन्
takṣan  (IE 7-1-2), ‘eight’.

tala|तल
tala,  cf. sa-tala (IE 8-5);<BR>surface of the ground.

taala|ताल
tāla  (IE 8-5), a palmyra palm;<BR>cf. sa-tālaka as an epithet of a gift village referring to the right of enjoying the trees by privileged tenants in some areas. 

taala|ताल
tāla  (SII 2), Tamil;<BR>a dish. (EI 21;<BR>SITI), Tamil;<BR>the treasury

talabhedyaa|तलभेद्या
tala-bhedyā  (IA 18), word of uncertain implication;<BR>mentioned with ghāṇaka, mallaka, vundhaka etc. (IA 18);<BR>cf. talabhedyāghāṇaka-mallaka-vundhaka-daṇḍadoṣa-prāpt-ādāya (Ind. Ant., Vol. XVIII, p. 83, text lines 19-20), epithet of gift village. See tala-bhoga.

talabhoga|तलभोग
tala-bhoga  (IA 7;<BR>SII 11-1), explained as ‘the enjoyment of sites of land’;<BR>really, ‘land granted for the maintenance of a temple at the time of its consecration’;<BR>same as tala-vāṭaka, tala-vṛtti, and probably also tala-bhedyā.

taaladhvaja|तालध्वज
Tāladhvaja  (BL), official designation of the governor of a territory;<BR>same as Gujarātī Tāl8ājā.

talaivan|तलैवन्
Talaivan  (SII 1), Tamil;<BR>a chief.

talaiyaari|तलैयारि
Talaiyāri  (SII 1), Tamil;<BR>same as Kannaḍa Talāri; a watchman. See Talavara.

talaka|तलक
talaka  (LP), ‘on the spot’. (EI 23), a territorial division.

talaaka|तलाक
tal8āka  (EI 14), same as taṭāka, taḍāga; a tank.

talapada|तलपद
tala-pada  (HRS), known from Caulukya records;<BR>lands fully assessed for revenue, as distinguished from estates which were held on condition of service or for a reduced lump assessment;<BR>explained as Gujarātī talpat, ‘land paying rent to the government’ (IA 11).

talapaaTa|तलपाट
tala-pāṭa  (SITI), Tamil;<BR>an army;<BR>armaments.

taalapatra|तालपत्र
tāla-patra,  Tamil olai (SITI);<BR>literally, ‘palmyra-leaf’;<BR>an order from the king or a person in authority. Cf. olai-ccādanam, ‘a document written on palm-leaf’;<BR>olai-ccampaḍam, ‘wages paid to the messenger who brings the olai to meet his expenses on the way’;<BR>also written as olai-ccambal8am, olai-ccammāḍam, etc.;<BR>same as nirūpa-ccambaḍam; cf. olai-nāyaka, ‘the chief secretary or the senior officer looking after correspondence.’

taalapaTTa|तालपट्ट
tāla-paṭṭa  (IA 15), probably the same as tāla-patra, meaning ‘an ear-ornament’.

talaprahaarin|तलप्रहारिन्
Talaprahārin  (EI 6), official designation;<BR>probably the same as Talārī or Kotwāl.

talaara|तलार
Talāra  (IE 8-2;<BR>EI 22;<BR>LP;<BR>BL;<BR>HD), administrator of a city or prefect of the city police;<BR>same as Talavara, Talārī or Kotwāl. Talavara of early South Indian inscriptions means a Rājasthānīya (a Duke or a viceroy) according to some  commentators and the Kotwāl or a city magistrate according to others. A subdivision of high class Khatris of the Punjab is called Tālwār. Cf. Tala-rakṣa or Tal-ārakṣa; also called Ārakṣika and Daṇḍapāśika. See Bhandarkar's List, No. 579;<BR>IHQ, 1960, p. 266.

talaaraabhaavya|तलाराभाव्य
talār-ābhāvya  (EI 11), tax for payment to the Talāra; according to some, Talāra is the Kotwāl and bhāvya or ābhāvya is what is called saṁbhāvanā, i. e. pāghḍī, and talār-ābhāvya is the pāghḍī money given to the Kotwāl (LP).

talaarii|तलारी
Talārī  (IE 8-2), Telugu-Kannaḍa;<BR>‘a village watchman’;<BR>same as Talāra.

talaarika|तलारिक
talārika  (ASLV), the office of the Talāra.

talaaraxa|तलारक्ष
Tal-ārakṣa  (EI 22), same as Talavara.

talaaTii|तलाटी
Talāṭī  (Ind. Ant., Vol. XII, p. 165, noted 38), a stipendiary (i. e. not hereditary) village accountant in the Kannaḍa-and Marāṭhī-speaking areas.

talavara|तलवर
Talavara  (IE 8-2;<BR>EI 20, 28), a title of the nobility or of subordinate rulers in some cases (a Rājasthānīya according to Vinayavijaya's Subodhikā commentary on the Jain Kalpasūtra);<BR>but the designation of the administrator of a city or of the police officer in charge of a city, according to some sources (Hemacandra explaining Talāra as Nagara-rakṣaka);<BR>cf. Talāra, Talārī, etc.;<BR>also Mahātalavara. (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXI, p. 78), cf. Talavara mentioned in the list of royal officials.

talavargika|तलवर्गिक
Talavargika  (EI 3), official designation.

talavaarikaa|तलवारिका
talavārikā,  cf. Kannaḍa tal8avārikā (EI 1), the villagewatchman's quit-rent;<BR>cf. Tal8avāra or Talāri (Tamil Talaiyāri), ‘a village-watchman’.

taalaavaarika|तालावारिक
Tālāvārika  (IA 12), official designation;<BR>same as either Talārī or Talāṭī (a stipendiary village-accountant in the Marāṭhī-and Kannaḍa-speaking areas).

talavaaTaka|तलवाटक
tala-vāṭaka  (EI 31), same as tala-pāṭaka or tala-vṛtti. But cf. tala-vāṭaka in tala-vāṭaka-vāstunā saha kṣetram, ‘a piece of land together with suburbs, gardens and homestead land’ (Select Inscriptions, p. 349, text line 18). The meaning here may also be ‘adjoining land’ which was probably the original implication of the expression.

talaavaaTaka|तलावाटक
Talāvāṭaka  (CII, Vol. III, p. 216;<BR>also p. 217 and note), possibly the superintendent of temple property (cf. tala-vāṭaka);<BR> same as Gujarātī Talāṭī (a petty revenue officer), according to some (HD).

talavRtti|तलवृत्ति
tala-vṛtti  (EI 13, 15, 21, 33;<BR>IA 7;<BR>SII 11-1;<BR>SITI), ‘endowment of the adjoining land’;<BR>land granted for the maintenance of a temple or deity at the time of its consecration;<BR>same as tala-bhoga, tala-vāṭaka, tala-pāṭaka.

taali|तालि
