veTakila|वेटकिल
Veṭakila  (IE 8-3);<BR>HD), probably ‘the bearer of vīṭikā (betel bīd8ā)’. See Vogel. Ant. Ch. St., p. 128. Cf. Vārgulika; also Paṭṭakila.

vetana|वेतन
vetana, vetanā  (SITI), wages (used along with veṭṭi, i. e.  Sanskrit viṣṭi or unpaid labour);<BR>probably wages for the labourers in the public works of the village.

veTha|वेठ
vē2ṭha  (IE 8-4), Kannaḍa;<BR>same as vē2ṇṭhē2, vē2ṭa, etc.;<BR>a small territorial unit.

vetrika|वेत्रिक
Vetrika  (EI 9;<BR>CII 4), explained by some as ‘the chamberlain’;<BR>cf. Yāṣṭika, Piśuna-vetrika.

vi|वि
vi  (CITD), abbreviation of Telugu vinnapamulu, representation or saying. It may stand for visālu (visā or vīsa) also.

vibhaaga|विभाग
vibhāga  (HRS), king's share of the output of mines;<BR>as suggested by the Arthaśāstra, rent from mines and from the private manufacturers of salt.

vibhava|विभव
vibhava  (IA 14), used in the sense of nirvāṇa (q. v.).

vibheda|विभेद
vibheda  (IE 8-4), subdivision of a khaṇḍa of Bhārata or Bhārata-varsa.

vibhoga|विभोग
vibhoga  (EI 16), holy ashes;<BR>same as vibhūti (q. v.).

vibhuuti|विभूति
vibhūti  (IA 12), holy ashes;<BR>same as vibhoga. (SITI), also called vibhūti-kāṇikkai in Tamil inscriptions;<BR>originally, voluntary contribution to a temple by the devotees while receiving the sacred ashes;<BR>later, it was collected as a tax.

vichaarakartR|विचारकर्तृ
Vicārakartṛ,  (EI 8), a supervisor.

vichitrakavitva|विचित्रकवित्व
vicitra-kavitva  (CITD), probably, a class of poetry like citra-kavitva, abounding in all kinds of highly artificial verses displaying the pedantry and verbal jugglery of the composer.

viDaalapadaka|विडालपदक
viḍālapadaka,  same as vivarṇa (q. v.).

vidha|विध
vidha  (SITI), variety, kind.

vidhaaraNaa|विधारणा
vidhāraṇā  (EI 1), same as paripanthanā, ‘creating obstacles’.

vidhipatra|विधिपत्र
vidhi-patra  (LP), a judgement.

vidhu|विधु
vidhu  (IE 7-1-2), ‘one’.

viDuurasaara|विडूरसार
viḍūra-sāra  (EI 3), same as vaiḍūrya.

vidvajjana|विद्वज्जन
vidvaj-jana  (SITI), a body of learned men.

vidyaa|विद्या
vidyā  (CII 4), the right knowledge. (IE 7-1-2), ‘fourteen’.

vidyaabhoga|विद्याभोग
vidyā-bhoga  (EI 18), same as vidy-ānubhoga and vidyā-dhana.

vidyaachaaraNa|विद्याचारण
vidyā-cāraṇa,  see cāraṇa (EI 3).

vidyaadhana|विद्याधन
vidyā-dhana  (HRS), explained as land assigned as a reward for learning;<BR>same as vidyā-bhoga and vidy-ānubhoga.

vidyaadharatoraNa|विद्याधरतोरण
vidyādhara-toraṇa  (SII 2), an ornamental arch probably depicting Vidyādharas;<BR>cf. makara-toraṇa. 

vidyaadhikaarin|विद्याधिकारिन्
Vidy-ādhikārin  (EI 11, 25;<BR>HD), officer in charge of a school or of schools;<BR>the director of education. Cf. Ep. Ind., Vol. XI, p. 314.

vidyaanubhoga|विद्यानुभोग
vidy-ānubhoga  (SITI), an endowment of land to a school for the encouragement of learning.

vidyaarthin|विद्यार्थिन्
Vidyārthin  (SITI), a student.

vidyaasthaana|विद्यास्थान
vidyā-sthāna  (EI 2;<BR>SII 2;<BR>SITI), an educational institution for higher studies;<BR>a college.

vigrahadrammavisovaka|विग्रहद्रम्मविसोवक
vigrahadramma-visovaka  (EI 1), name of a coin;<BR>the latter part of the name (i. e. visovaka = viṁśopaka) suggests that it was one-twentieth of the vigraha-dramma in value.

vigrahapaaladramma|विग्रहपालद्रम्म
vigrahapāla-dramma  (EI 1), name of a coin;<BR>same as vigrahapāla-satka-dramma, vigrahapālīya-dramma.

vigrahapaalasatkadramma|विग्रहपालसत्कद्रम्म
vigrahapāla-satka-dramma  (EI 1), see vigrahapālīya-dramma, etc.

vigrahapaaliiyadramma|विग्रहपालीयद्रम्म
vigrahapālīya-dramma  (EI 1;<BR>CII 4), name of a coin apparently so called after a king named Vigrahapāla.

vigrahatungiiyadramma|विग्रहतुङ्गीयद्रम्म
vigrahatuṅgīya-dramma  (EI 1;<BR>CII 4), name of a coin apparently so called after a king named Vigrahatuṅga.

vihaara|विहार
vihāra  (EI 22, 25;<BR>CII 3, 4;<BR>BL), a Buddhist or Jain monastery or temple or convent (EI 35). (HA), wandering of a Jain monk;<BR>also a Jain temple.

vihaarakaaraka|विहारकारक
Vihārakāraka,  cf. Prakrit Viharakarahvaa (CII 2-1), ‘one who builds a monastery’;<BR>same as Vihārasvāmin; explained by some as ‘the superintendent of monastery’ (ML).

viharamaaNajina|विहरमाणजिन
Viharamāṇa-Jina  (HA), a Jina at present living in other kṣetras.

vihaarapaala|विहारपाल
Vihārapāla,  ‘the manager of a monastery’ (Select Inscriptions, p. 345).

vihaarasvaamin|विहारस्वामिन्
Vihārasvāmin  (EI 8, 33;<BR>CII 3;<BR>BL;<BR>LL), ‘the master of a monastery’;<BR>the builder or owner of a monastyer. Cf. Vihārakāraka.

vihaarasvaaminii|विहारस्वामिनी
Vihārasvāminī  (CII 3;<BR>IA 11), the feminine form of Vihārasvāmin; wife of a Vihārasvāmin or the female owner of a vihāra.

vihaarayaatraa|विहारयात्रा
vihāra-yātrā  (CII 1), a pleasure-tour.

vihaarikaa|विहारिका
vihārikā  (EI 23, 27), derived from vihāra, vihāraka; a small vihāra or monastery.

vihiMsaa|विहिंसा
vihiṁsā  (CII 1), hurting, injuring.

vihita|विहित
vihita  (CII 1), established;<BR>settled. 

vihRtayati|विहृतयति
vihṛtayati,  ‘[he]<BR>wastes’ (Select Inscriptions, p. 245).

vijaalayitavya|विजालयितव्य
vijālayitavya,  to be untied (Select Inscriptions, p. 238).

vijaaTin|विजाटिन्
Vijāṭin  (IA 11), cf. Vijāṭi-vidyādhara, ‘a Vidyādhara unwinding his head-dress’.

vijaya|विजय
vijaya,  used in Kannaḍa inscriptions in the sense of ‘going in state, going in a triumpal procession, making a state procession, making a state progress through one's dominions’ (Ep. Ind., Vol. V, p. 223, note 6;<BR>Vol. VI, p. 51, note 5). (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXI, p. 18), Od8iyā, etc.;<BR>used in Od8iyā inscriptions in the sense of ‘stay’. (IA 7), cf. vijaya-rājya-saṁvalsara, vijaya-saṁvatsara, vijaya-kaṭaka, vijaya-skandhāvāra, etc. Cf. śrī-vijaya and śrī-vijaya-śiva.

vijayaa|विजया
vijayā  (IA 26), same as su-di 11 or the eleventh tithi.

vijayaabhiSheka|विजयाभिषेक
vijay-ābhiṣeka  (SITI), being crowned as a victor;<BR>same as vīr-ābhiṣeka.

vijayachandra|विजयचन्द्र
vijaya-candra  (SII 2), name of an ornament.

vijayaadashamii|विजयादशमी
vijayā-daśamī  (EI 31), Āśvina-sudi 10.

vijayaka|विजयक
vijayaka  (LP), same as vijaya, victory.

vijayakaTaka|विजयकटक
vijaya-kaṭaka  (EI 2;<BR>LP), ‘the victorious camp’;<BR>the royal camp or capital.

vijayalekha|विजयलेख
vijaya-lekha  (EI 9), a royal record.

vijayaraajaTanka|विजयराजटङ्क
vijayarāja-ṭaṅka  (CII 4), name of a coin apparently so called after a ruler named Vijayarāja who was its issuer.

vijayasaptamii|विजयसप्तमी
vijaya-saptamī  (EI 3), name of a tithi.

vijayashaasana|विजयशासन
vijaya-śāsana  (EI 33), any royal record (cf. śāsana);<BR>sometimes the same as dharma-vijaya-śāsana (q. v.).

vijayashiva|विजयशिव
vijaya-śiva,  cf. śrī-vijaya-śiva-Mṛgeśavarman, etc. (The Successors of the Sātavāhanas, pp. 261 ff.);<BR>an honorific prefixed to royal names. See śrī, vijaya, śiva.

vijayastambha|विजयस्तम्भ
vijaya-stambha  (SITI), pillar of victory.

vijayavaijayika|विजयवैजयिक
vijaya-vaijayika,  victory;<BR>sometimes used as an adjective qualifying the regnal date (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXV, p. 152, text line 5;<BR>cf. ibid., Vol. XXXII, p. 88).

vijayavandaapanaa|विजयवन्दापना
vijaya-vandāpanā  (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 12), Od8iyā;<BR>a levy;<BR>presents to be offered to the king or landlord on the occasion of his victorious return from a campaign or for the preparation of a campaign;<BR>cf. vandāpanā.

vijayavixepa|विजयविक्षेप
vijaya-vikṣepa  (IA 13), epithet of a place where a king was staying. See vikṣepa. 

vijita|विजित
vijita  (CII 1), dominions.

viJNaanin|विज्ञानिन्
Vijñānin  (EI 20, 32), an artisan;<BR>same as Śilpin; epithet of an artisan who is usually the engraver of an inscription.

viJNaapanaa|विज्ञापना
vijñāpanā  (IA 10), also called vijñapti; an application;<BR>a request;<BR>cf. Kannaḍa binna-vattaḷē2 = Sanskrit vijñāpana-patra (SII 11-1).

viJNapti|विज्ञप्ति
Vijñapti  (EI 29), official designation. Cf. Ājñapti, etc.

viJNapti|विज्ञप्ति
vijñapti  (SITI), sometimes also spelt vijñāpti; petitioning to the king (cf. vijñāpanā);<BR>an officer who brings the petition of the subjects to the king's notice. (EI 23;<BR>SII 2), also called vijñāpya, an application or petition.

viJNaapi|विज्ञापि
vi-jñāpi  (CII 3, etc.), verb used in connection with the making of a grant by the king at the request, or on the advice, of somcone who was the real donor.

viJNaapya|विज्ञाप्य
vijñāpya  (EI 23), cf. Tamil viṇṇappam (SII 1), a petition;<BR>also called vijñapti.

vikara|विकर
vikara,  cf. vikara-padāni (LP), a small present, a bonus;<BR>cf. Gujarātī pān-sopārī. (LP), cf. vikara-pada explained as ‘miscellancous expenses’.

vikaraNapaTTaka|विकरणपट्टक
vikaraṇa-paṭṭaka  (LP), a merket-tax contract.

vikramaaditya|विक्रमादित्य
Vikramāditya  (IE 8-2), see āditya.

vikRti|विकृति
vikṛti  (IE 7-1-2), ‘twentythree’.

vixepa|विक्षेप
vikṣepa  (IA 7, 13), cf. vijaya-vikṣepa used as an epithet of the place whence a royal charter was issued;<BR>cf. vijaya-vikṣepāt Bharukaccha-vāsakāt; wrongly interpreted as ‘a camp or cantonment’ (IA 17). See also Vaikṣepika.

vilabdhi|विलब्धि
vilabdhi  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 30), used in the Rājataraṅgiṇī, probably in the sense of presents offered to the king or the stolen property recovered;<BR>explaiened as ‘an assignment’. See Vailabdhika.

vilahaNaa|विलहणा
vilahaṇā  (LP), probably, an escort;<BR>suite.

vilaasinii|विलासिनी
Vilāsinī  (EI 33), same as Devadāsī; also called Gaṇikā, etc.

vilekhaka|विलेखक
Vilekhaka  (EI 22), an engraver. Cf. Ullekhaka, utkṛ.

vilok|विलोक्
vi-lok,  cf. vilokyante (LP), ‘are being searched for’, used in respect of one who is in search of money in times of difficulty.

vimaana|विमान
vimāna  (SITI), the pinnacle or upper structure over the sanctum of a temple;<BR>the central shrine of a temple (SII 3);<BR>also called śrī-vimāna (SII 13);<BR>same as garbha-gṛha. (EI 3, 23), a shrine.  (IA 9), the steeple tower over a shrine;<BR>also called stupī.

viMshatika|विंशतिक
viṁśatika,  regarded as equal to 20 māṣas (JNSI, Vol. XVI, p. 52);<BR>cf. viṁśopaka.

viMsatima|विंसतिम
viṁsatima  (CII 3), used for viṁśatitama, twentieth.

viMsopaka|विंसोपक
viṁsopaka  (EI 1), corrupt form of viṁśopaka, a copper coin which was (1/20) of the standard silver coin in value.

viMshopaka|विंशोपक
viṁśopaka  (IE 8-6, 8-8;<BR>EI 29, 30;<BR>CII 4), a copper coin which was one-twentieth of the standard silver coin in value;<BR>cf. Viśālapriya-viṁśopaka (IE 8-8);<BR>Varāhakīya-viṁśopaka (EI 1);<BR>Vṛṣaviṁśopaka (q. v.);<BR>a land measure equal to one twentieth of the standard land measure. See vīsa, viṁsopaka, vīsovā, visovaka. Cf. viśopaka (LP), supposed to be the same as vighā, a measure of land equal to 20 vasas [in Gujarat].

viiNaa|वीणा
vīṇā  (ASLV), a musical instrument. Cf. vīṇai-kkāṇi (SITI), right of playing on the vīṇā before the god in a temple during worship.

vinamu|विनमु
vinamu  (CITD), Telugu;<BR>an unknown weight greater than a cinna or cinnamu, otherwise called sinna.

vinaasha|विनाश
vināśa  (LP), ‘not doing anything at all’.

vinaashin|विनाशिन्
vināśin,  cf. a-kūra-chullaka-vināśi-khaṭvā-vāsa (IE 8-5), an attendant, or fuel. The villagers were obliged to supply it to the touring officers of the king.

vinaShTaraajya|विनष्टराज्य
vinaṣṭa-rājya  (IE), same as gata-rājya or atīta-rājya, someone's sovereignty that was a thing of the past.

vinaya|विनय
vinaya  (IE 8-8;<BR>EI 30), fines. (EI 13), same as indriya-jaya.

vinayadhara|विनयधर
Vinayadhara  (LL), Buddhist;<BR>one who has learnt the Vinaya texts by heart.

vinaayaka|विनायक
Vināyaka  (LL), a teacher of the vinaya texts;<BR>a name of the god Gaṇeśa.

vinaayakahoma|विनायकहोम
Vināyaka-homa  (EI 26), a rite;<BR>same as Gaṇeśa-homa.

vindu|विन्दु
vindu  (EI 7-1-2), also spelt bindu; ‘cypher’. (SII 2), a flaw in diamonds.

vinibaddhakaara|विनिबद्धकार
Vinibaddhakāra,  see Vinibandhakāra.

vinibandhakaara|विनिबन्धकार
Vinibandhakāra  (EI 8), same as Vinibaddhakāra; explained as ‘one who registers [a document]’;<BR>really, ‘one who cancels the registration [of a document]’ (Select Inscriptions, p. 202).

vinirgata|विनिर्गत
vinirgata  (EI 7), cf. Pāṭaliputra-bhaṭṭāgrahāra-vinirgata (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXII, p. 122, text line 16);<BR>‘hailing from’, or more suitably ‘one whose family hails from’. When a  locality called Aṭṭamūla is described as vinirgata from Bṛhaddhaṭṭa, it seems to mean that the former was originally a part of the latter (ibid., Vol. XXXIII, p. 151).

viniyoga|विनियोग
viniyoga  (SITI), an employment;<BR>use;<BR>expenditure. (EI 24), a tax;<BR>cf. Tamil vāśal-viniyogam (SITI), same as vāśal-paṇam; also sabhā-viniyoga (SII 13).

viniyukta|विनियुक्त
Viniyukta  (HD), an officer probably under the Āyuktaka; same as Viniyuktaka (q. v.), etc. Cf. Ep. Ind., Vol. XV, p. 256.

viniyuktaka|विनियुक्तक
Viniyuktaka  (CII 3, 4), an official title meaning a smaller administrative officer serving under a higher officer;<BR>an official probably under the Āyuktaka; same as Viniyukta. Cf. Ep. Ind., Vol. XI, pp. 80, 83. (IE 8-3), mentioned along with Tadāyuktaka. Cf. Tadviniyuktaka.

vipravinodin|विप्रविनोदिन्
Vipra-vinodin  (SITI), a class of Brāhmaṇas who were adepts in jugglery and magical practices.

viira|वीर
vīra  (IE 8-2), sometimes prefixed to the names of kings and even treated as almost an integral part of the name;<BR>cf. pratāpa, vīra-pratāpa, etc. (EI 3), Jain;<BR>same as Mahāvīra. Cf. vīra-kal8 (SITI), also written vīra-kkal8, vīra-gal8; a herostone;<BR>an inscribed or uninscribed stone pillar raised in honour of a person who died in fighting for a good cause.

viirabhadra|वीरभद्र
Vīrabhadra  (SITI), also called Vīramuṣṭi; member of a militant class of temple servants who diligently protected the properties and rights of the temples. Cf. Vīrakośa.

viiraabhiSheka|वीराभिषेक
vīr-ābhiṣeka  (EI 18;<BR>SITI), ‘anointment as a hero’.

viirabhoga|वीरभोग
vīra-bhoga  (SITI), land assigned for the maintenance of a warrior.

viiragal|वीरगल्
vīra-gal8  (CII 4), also written vīra-kkal8. See vīra.

viirakkal|वीरक्कल्
vīra-kkal8  (CII 4), also written vīra-gal8, a stone pillar raised in memory of heroes. See vīra.

viirakosha|वीरकोश
Vīrakośa,  official designation (The Successor of the Sātavāhanas, p. 110, note 2);<BR>mentioned along with Hastikośa as an officer related to a district;<BR>probably, an officer in charge of the local soldiers or infantry men. Cf. Vīrabhadra, etc.

virakta|विरक्त
Virakta  (SITI), an ascetic;<BR>a man free from worldly attachment;<BR>a recluse of the Śaiva order. 

viralarishi|विरलरिशि
viral-ariśi  (ASLV), rice provided for goldsmiths for amputating the last two fingers of the wives of farmers.

viiramaalaa|वीरमाला
vīra-mālā,  cf. vīra-mālai (SITI), a poem in praise of a warrior.

viiramuShTi|वीरमुष्टि
Vīramuṣṭi  (SITI), same as Vīrabhadra.

viirapaTTa|वीरपट्ट
vīra-paṭṭa  (SII 2;<BR>SITI), an ornament;<BR>a front plate, probably a plate worn on the forehead by distinguished warriors.

viirapaTTaNa|वीरपट्टण
vīra-paṭṭaṇa  (SITI), also called er8i-vīra-paṭṭaṇam; a mercantile town inhabited by the er8i-vīrar.

viiraprataapa|वीरप्रताप
Vīra-pratāpa  (IE 8-2), cf. Vīra and Pratāpa.

viirashaasana|वीरशासन
vīra-śāsana  (SITI), CITD) explained by some as the same as vīrakal8, ‘a hero stone’, established for commemorating the death of soldiers on the battle-field;<BR>a grant made by the king in recognition of the heroic activity of a person;<BR>a charter recording the grant of land or other property to a warrior.

viirasheSha|वीरशेष
vīra-śeṣa,  cf. vīra-śeṣai (SITI);<BR>probably, the provision made for the descendants of dead warriors;<BR>sometimes explained as a tax (EI 22). Cf. mṛtyuka-vṛtti, rakta-mānya, etc.

viirasiMhaasana|वीरसिंहासन
vīra-siṁhāsana  (SII 1), the throne of heroes.

viirayaatrika|वीरयात्रिक
Vīra-yātrika  (IA 17;<BR>HD), an official designation;<BR>probably, the leader of an expedition;<BR>a person taking part in a military expedition. See Vogel, Ant. Ch. St., p. 129.

viruupaaxapati|विरूपाक्षपति
Virūpākṣa-pati,  cf. Prakrit Virūpakha-pati (EI 20), epithet of the god Mahāsena or Kārttikeya, Virūpākṣa probably being the name of a host of which the god was conceived as the leader.

viisa|वीस
vīsa  (IE 8-8;<BR>EI 5), name of a coin (JNSI, Vol. XXVI, pp. 127ff.);<BR>cf. lokkiya-vīsa, probably meaning ‘a vīsa minted at Lokkiguṇḍi’;<BR>Sanskrit viṁśa, viṁśaka, viṁśatika, or viṁśopaka. (Ep. Ind., Vol. VI, p. 232, note 6), Telugu-Kannaḍa;<BR>(1/16) of a haṇa (paṇa); but (1/20) of the standard coin in value essentially. (CITD), also called visā, visya, visāmu; Telugu-Kannaḍa;<BR>the fraction (1/10);<BR>gold equal in weight to one grain of rice;<BR>(1/256) of a Hun or Pagoda; 40 palas; a measure of land equal nearly to 2 acres.

visaa|विसा
visā,  also spelt visāmu (CITD), see vīsa.

viShaharabhoga|विषहरभोग
viṣahara-bhoga  (SITI), also called viṣa-vṛtti; land set apart for the support of a poison-doctor.

viisalapriyadramma|वीसलप्रियद्रम्म
vīsala-priya-dramma,  also called vīsala-prī-dramma; cf. jīrṇaviśvamalla-priya, etc. (A. R. Ep., 1957-58, Nos. B 490-92). 

visaMsthula|विसंस्थुल
visaṁsthula  (LP), agitated, unsteady.

visatiaThuuprastha|विसतिअठूप्रस्थ
visatiaṭhū-prastha  (IA 18), a levy;<BR>probably viṁśatisatkaprastha, ‘one out of 20 prasthas.’

viShavRtti|विषवृत्ति
viṣa-vṛtti  (SITI), same as viṣahara-bhoga.

viShaya|विषय
viṣaya  (EI 8-4), a district;<BR>often a kingdom or territory;<BR>sometimes a viṣaya was included in a maṇḍala; but, in some cases, a maṇḍala was included in a viṣaya; at times maṇḍala and viṣaya were synonymous. (IE 8-5;<BR>EI 30;<BR>CII 3, 4;<BR>BL;<BR>SITI), a district;<BR>cf. viṣaya-suṅka (EI 24), the tax of a district;<BR>Viṣaya-vyavahārin, officer in the service of a district. (ASLV), same as nirvṛtti or koṭṭam; an administrative division. (IE 8-4;<BR>CII 4), sometimes used in a wider sense to indicate ‘a country’. (IE 7-1-2), ‘five’.

visaya|विसय
visaya  (CITD), same as Telugu visā, visāmu.

viShayabhogika|विषयभोगिक
Viṣaya-bhogika  (EI 28), probably, the ināmdār or ināmdārs of a district.

viShayabhuubhuj|विषयभूभुज्
Viṣaya-bhūbhuj  (IA 15), explained as ‘a native ruler’ as opposed to a ‘foreign conqueror.’

viShayadaana|विषयदान
viṣaya-dāna  (HRS), name of a tax (Ep. Ind., Vol. XI, p. 21;<BR>Vol. XIV, p. 196), probably, a regional tax or taxes realisable from a particular district;<BR>known from Gāhaḍavāla records;<BR>cf. viṣayālī.

viShayadaanika|विषयदानिक
Viṣaya-dānika  (EI 7;<BR>CII 4), collector of the levy called viṣaya-dāna; or a district officer in charge of gifts or an officer in charge of gift lands in a district;<BR>or the collector of the revenue of a district.

viShayaadhikaraNa|विषयाधिकरण
Viṣay-ādhikaraṇa  (EI 23, 31), administrative officer of a district;<BR>the district administrator's office.

viShayaadhipati|विषयाधिपति
Viṣay-ādhipati,  same as Viṣayapati (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIV, p. 219).

viShayakaraNa|विषयकरण
Viṣaya-karaṇa  (EI 32), probably, the chief scribe at the office of the administrators of a district.

viShayaalii|विषयाली
viṣayālī  (EI 33), name of a tax;<BR>probably the same as viṣaya-dāna.

viShayaamaatya|विषयामात्य
Viṣay-āmātya  (EI 27, 30), governor of a district;<BR>an Amātya in charge of a viṣaya or an Amātya under the Viṣayapati. See Ep. Ind., Vol. XXX, p. 64. 

viShayaNa|विषयण
viṣayaṇa  (EI 1), meaning doubtful.

viShayapaala|विषयपाल
Viṣayapāla  (EI 28), same as Viṣayapati.

viShayapati|विषयपति
Viṣayapati  (IE 8-3;<BR>CII 3, 4;<BR>BL;<BR>HD), governor of a district called viṣaya; distinguished from Viṣaya-vyāpṛtaka; same as Viṣay-ādhipati. Cf. Ind. Ant., Vol. V, p. 114. See Viṣayeśa, Viṣayeśvara, etc.

viShayavyaapRtaka|विषयव्यापृतक
Viṣaya-vyāpṛtaka  (IE 8-3), sometimes distinguished from the Viṣayapati; an officer associated with the administration of a district (cf. Viṣaya-vyavahārin).

viShayavyavahaarin|विषयव्यवहारिन्
Viṣaya-vyavahārin  (IE 8-3), an administrative officer in a district or a member of the district council. Cf. Viṣaya-vyavahārin, Viṣayika, Viṣayin.

viShayesha|विषयेश
Viṣayeśa  (HD), same as Viṣayapati, etc.

viShayeshvara|विषयेश्वर
Viṣayeśvara  (EI 26), same as Viṣayapati, etc.

viShayika|विषयिक
Viṣayika  (EI 24), same as Viṣaya-vyavahārin; cf. Viṣayin.

viShayikaadhikaarika|विषयिकाधिकारिक
Viṣayik-ādhikārika  (EI 32), taken to be a single official designation;<BR>probably Viṣayika and Ādhikārika.

viShayin|विषयिन्
Viṣayin  (EI 24, 32), possibly, the same as Viṣaya-vyavahārin; cf. Viṣayika.

viseNima|विसेणिम
viseṇima, viseṇimā  (CII 4), a tax, also called viseṇimādāya (EI 21).

visheShaadaaya|विशेषादाय
viśeṣ-ādāya  (SITI), also called viśeṣ-āya; a special group of taxes.

visheShaaya|विशेषाय
viśeṣ-āya  (SITI), same as viśeṣ-ādāya (q. v.).

vishikha|विशिख
viśikha  (BL), name of a kind of building.

vishiirNa|विशीर्ण
viśīrṇa,  wearing out, worn out part of a building;<BR>cf. bhagnaviśīrṇa-samāracana (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIV, p. 144).

vishiSha|विशिष
Viśiṣa  (IE 8-3;<BR>EI 1, 30), probably, the governor or commander of a fort;<BR>a word of uncertain derivation.

viShNubaahu|विष्णुबाहु
viṣṇu-bāhu,  see hari-bāhu (IE 7-1-2), ‘four’.

viShNugRha|विष्णुगृह
viṣṇu-gṛha  (SITI), a Viṣṇu temple.

viShNupada|विष्णुपद
viṣṇu-pada  (IE 7-1-2), ‘cypher’.

viShNutithi|विष्णुतिथि
viṣṇu-tithi  (IA 19), same as Jyaiṣṭha-sudi 11.

viShNushraadha|विष्णुश्राध
viṣṇu-śrādha  (Ep. Ind., Vol. XXXIV, p. 37), an expression of doubtful meaning.

viisovaa|वीसोवा
vīsovā  (CII 4), name of a coin;<BR>a land measure;<BR>same as viṁśopaka.

visovaka|विसोवक
visovaka  (EI 1), corrupt form of viṁśopaka (q. v.).

viShTapa|विष्टप
viṣṭapa  (IE 7-1-2), ‘three’.

vistaraNa|विस्तरण
vistaraṇa  (EI 1), meaning doubtful. 

viShTi|विष्टि
viṣṭi  (IE 8-5;<BR>CII 4;<BR>HRS), labour which the villagers were obliged to provide to the king or landlord on occasions;<BR>unpaid labour;<BR>forced labour. Cf. veṭṭi (SITI), unpaid labour for public works in the village without time or other limits;<BR>usually mentioned along with vetana as veṭṭi-vetanai. Cf. veṭṭi-ccor8u, the obligation of feeding veṭṭi labourers free of cost;<BR>also cf. Tamil veṭṭi-pāṭṭam (EI 24), explained as ‘a kind of tax’;<BR>tax in lieu of viṣṭi.

vishuddhi|विशुद्धि
viśuddhi,  cf. viśuddhiṁ yāvat (LP), ‘till the account is clear’.

viShuva|विषुव
viṣuva  (CII 4;<BR>SII 1), the autumnal or vernal equinox;<BR>also called viṣuvat (q. v.).

viShuvat|विषुवत्
viṣuvat  (IE 7-1-2), ‘two’. Cf. viṣuva.

vishva|विश्व
viśva  (IE 7-1-2), same as viśvedevāḥ, ‘thirteen.’

vishvachakra|विश्वचक्र
viśvacakra  (EI 24), name of a mahādāna.

vishvedevaaH|विश्वेदेवाः
viśvedevāḥ  (IE 7-1-2), ‘thirteen’;<BR>same as viśva.

